member.name: T:SFSdotNet.Framework.Web.Mvc.FileUploadJsonResult
member.summary: A JsonResult with ContentType of text/html and the serialized object contained within textarea tags
member.remarks: It is not possible to upload files using the browser's XMLHttpRequest object. So the jQuery Form Plugin uses a hidden iframe element. For a JSON response, a ContentType of application/json will cause bad browser behavior so the content-type must be text/html. Browsers can behave badly if you return JSON with ContentType of text/html. So you must surround the JSON in textarea tags. All this is handled nicely in the browser by the jQuery Form Plugin. But we need to overide the default behavior of the JsonResult class in order to achieve the desired result.
